data.title: Faculty, Staff and Ph.D. Students
data.meta_description: UGA Grady College faculty are experts and thought-leaders in journalism, public relations, advertising and entertainment studies.
data.text:
Faculty & Staff

Our faculty are experts in their fields of research and study, thought-leaders in the industries they serve and dedicated to inspiring our students through critical thinking, ethical reasoning and skills building. They are frequently called on by media to apply their knowledge to what is going on in the world today.

Additional information

Explore faculty openings at Grady College and celebrate those who have retired from our College.

David Clementson, asst. professor in public relations, is quoted in U.S. News and World Reports about President Biden’s responses to media questions about his mental health: Team Biden Takes on the Press (Feb. 14, 2024.)

Booker T. Mattison, associate professor in our Department of Entertainment and Media Studies, talks with WABE about his roles directing films and teaching filmmaking. His interview starts around the 10 minute mark. (Jan. 16, 2024)

Jonathan Peters, head of the Department of Journalism, talks with AP about incidents of governments suing journalists and residents for making records requests becoming more common (Dec. 19, 2023.)

David Clementson, asst. professor in AdPR, talks about George Santos and his recent expulsion from Congress. Clementson’s research specializes in experiments testing how politicians dodge reporters’ questions. (Dec. 4, 2023)

Congratulations to Nick Chiles, our Writer in Residence in our Dept. of Journalism, on having “Disruptive Thinking,” a book he co-wrote with T.D. Jakes, on the New York Times bestseller list. The book spent four weeks on the Advice, How-To & Miscellaneous list.

Congratulations to Sanghoon Lee of our UGA MFA Film faculty, on the availability of the film “Art & Pep” on Peacock June 1. Lee was director of photography for this LGBTQ+ documentary. (June 1, 2023)

Dean Charles Davis was interviewed for an article published in Atlanta Magazine titled, “Journalism is struggling. In Atlanta, new indie outlets are finding ways to make it work-and brining in important voices.”

Congratulations to Mark E. Johnson, senior lecture and chief technology officer, on being named the 2023 NPPA Educator of the Year. (March 7, 2023)

Professor in Public Relations, talks with Kera News about how fans of Turkish dramas are refocusing social media efforts on helping victims of the earthquakes. (Feb. 16, 2023)

Talks with Fox News about the controversial angle some media have taken in reporting about Georgia’s new election law. (Feb. 10, 2023)
